  "prompt": "What if the Man of Steel flew directly in to the Sun's center? Would so much heat be too much? Steel does melt around 1370 C, after all.",
  "response": "The Man of Steel, also known as Superman, is a fictional character with superhuman abilities. His powers include immense strength, flight, invulnerability, and more. These abilities are not constrained by the properties of actual steel, but rather are depicted as far surpassing the limitations of real-world materials.\n\nIn numerous adaptations and comic storylines, Superman's invulnerability allows him to withstand extreme conditions, including temperatures and pressures far beyond those found on Earth. The core of the Sun is incredibly hot, reaching temperatures of around 15 million degrees Celsius. In reality, any material, including steel, would disintegrate under such conditions. However, Superman's fictional invulnerability would enable him to survive and even function within the Sun's core without being harmed.\n\nComic book physics often operate under different rules than real-world physics, allowing characters like Superman to perform feats that defy scientific principles. Ultimately, Superman's ability to withstand the temperatures and pressures of the Sun is a reflection of his status as an iconic superhero with nearly limitless capabilities, rather than a comparison to the melting point of steel or other real-world materials.",
